How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Mark's semen was very thick, but after his vasectomy it was also what? Choices:  A: blank B: sparse C: thin D: clear E: free flowing<n>Output:		clear<n><n><n>https://www.kaggle.com/c/jeopardy-dev-challenge/train/problems<n><n>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the multiple choice question.<n>Input:Mary had 89 stick...<n>    How much does Zach need to ear...<n>       ...he babysitting for...<n>Output:6<n>       ..is Josh’s mom gives...<n>    Output:3<n>           ..the final round to...<n>Output:27<n>-------------------------------------------------------------------------------<n><n>### Instruciton:Answer the multiple choice <n>question.Input:...<n>Input:... If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Where would you put a folding chair if you do not plan to use it and you do not have any large doors in your house? Choices:  A: roof B: school C: beach D: closet E: garage<n>Output:		 C<n><n>Input: How many stickers does Shay have? Shay has 1 square with the number 14, 2 squares with the number 44, 2 squares of the number 2, 1 square with the letter A.<n>Output: 222<n><n>Input : Alice ate k = 2/3 of pizza that weighed 6 pounds and she threw the rest of pizza away.. How much of the pizza that she ate weighed?<n>Output : 3 pounds<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Though it stayed strictly indoors, the small dog felt like it had all the space in the world in the what? Choices:  A: living room B: dog park C: basket D: small apartment E: big house<n>Output:		C<n><n>---<n><n>### Solution:<n>This is a simple case of **DP** technique.  I first considered a 2-state problem where I have to determine if I should buy the bike or not.<n>> In the first part I bought the bike.<n>> In the 2nd part I didn't get paid enough and in other words I don't have enough money to buy the bike.<n><n>If you go through the problem statement I don't have access to the data.  However, the question could be formulated such that I know the numbers of animals I have before.<n><n>It is now easy to find out my total number of animals and animals without legs then it gets trivial to find the number of animals with legs if I know my total number of animals.<n><n>### Time Complexity<n>This problem has to do with the problem of recursion and then the running of the computation.  In the first part I used the recursive method to compute my number of animals with legs in other words I'll use the same procedure for two different cases, one where I buy the bike, other where I don't.  This will take me n calls to the function to arrive at my final answer.<n>The running time is thus `O(2^n)` where n is the number of calls to the recursive routine.<n><n>The cost of the recursive call is negligible and this is `O(1)` as well.<n>So the running cost is simply `O(2^N)`<n><n>### Space Complexity<n>This is again quite simple.  If I take the number of calls to be n, then I'll need another n space in my memory, so my total memory complexity for both cases `O(2*n)`<n><n>Hope this helps!  Thanks.

Write a function that splits the string on spaces and returns an array of the first 25 characters of each segment. <n><n>Instructions: "hi, how are you?, great."<n>Output:<n>[hi, how are you?]<n>[great.]<n><n>### Code:<n>Instructions_:<n><n>function solution(str){<n>    let words=str.split(" "); <n>    let ret=[]<n>    for (let i=0;i<25;i++){<n>        if (words.length==i+1){<n>            ret.push(words[i])<n>        }else{<n>            ret.push("...")<n>        }<n>    }<n>    return ret<n>}<n>solution("hi, how are you, how are you?, fine, great. Choices:  A: dicks sporting goods B: sporting event C: mall D: sears E: sporting goods store<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: I asked an artist to tattoo a sunset into my left forearm. The artist placed a beautiful orange yin yang sunset on my left forearm and asked me how it looked. I told the artist the sunset looked great where she placed it, and that the tattoo was perfect! There were two minor issues with the tattoo's placement, however. The artist placed the moon on my upper forearm, and the artist placed the sun on the same side of my forearm where the moon is located. Both the moon and the sun were positioned on the same side of the forearm I asked the artist to tattoo into.  How many different pieces of equipment should be in the set?<n>Output: 5<n>-------------------<n>###Instruction<n><n>Please write down the code of all functions you designed and explain the logic behind them before you do the execution.<n><n>### Problem 1: Mary had 8 stickers. She used 3 large sticker on the front page of the journal and 7 sticker each on 6 other pages of the journal.  How many stickers was remain.<n><n>### Solution<n>```c#<n>const int k = 89;<n>const int n = 14; //no of page.<n>const int s1 = 3; //number of lg sticker.<n>const int s2 = 7; //no of sticker required on the rest of the pages.<n>int sum = 0;<n>int i,n1,sum1,temp;<n>    for(i = 0; i <= n-1; i++){<n>        if((i==0)){<n>            if(((k-(k/s1))+s1==j)){<n>                n1=j;<n>            }<n>            else{<n>                n1=k-(k%s1);<n>            }<n>            sum+=k%n1;<n>        }<n>        else{<n>            if(((n-1-i)*s2==k%n1))<n>            {<n>                sum1=k%n1; //find remaining<n>                temp=s1+(s2*i-temp*i);<n>                sum=sum+temp;<n>            }<n>        }<n>    }<n>    Console.WriteLine(sum());<n>```<n><n># Problem

Remember to use only 0 or 1 or both based on the value of an element.<n><n>def sumOfArrays(n,a,sum=0):<n>    for i in range(n+1):<n>        if a[i] == 1:<n>            sum+=1<n>        if a[sum] == 0:<n>            sum+=n + 1<n>    return sum<n>

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:What is the opposite of hosting a crowd? Choices:  A: few people B: pay debts C: individual D: single person E: small group<n>Output:		F: Many People<n><n>Input: Aaron likes math. Aaron is a big fan of football. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Where did the compassionate farmer allow the heifer to reside during her last days? Choices:  A: cattle ranch B: countryside C: grocery store D: slaughterhouse E: dairy farm<n>Output:		E<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Lilly owns the only kosher deli in the area.  She isn't in a heavily populated area.  Where might she live? Choices:  A: food court B: jerusalem C: new york city D: jewish community E: town<n>Output:		<n><n>*If correct select 1: A* *If incorrect select 1: B*<n><n>*If correct selection please select 5* *If incorrect selection please select 4*<n><n>**Solution:**<n><pre><n>-A-<n>If Correct select 1: A<n>If Incorrect select 1: B <n><n>The correct selection is A<n><n>**Solution**<n></pre><n><n>-B-<n>If Correct select -5-<n>If Incorrect select -4-<n><n>The correct selection should be E. There is not many Jewish communities in this area.<n><n>**Solution-<n></pre><n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. She used 3 large and 7 stickers for 6 pages. She has 6 stickers for each 6 pages, which totals 36. So she has 44 stickers.<n><n>The second multiple choice question requires us figuring out how much money Zach needs in order to buy a new bike. The total price of a bike is $100. His allowance is $5/week, which is multiplied by 15, then subtracted from $100, which yields a result of 10. His neighbor will pay him 7 dollars/hour to babysit for a total of 2 hours. The total is 14. In order to make up the $100, he needs to earn another 56 dollars. So he needs an addition of 66 dollars.<n><n>The next multiple choice question requires us determining the total of the number of legs the kangaroo and goats have. 89 + 3 = 92 and 92 + 80 = 172 and 172 + 4= 176 which totals 322. We subtract 20, the number of kangaroos, from 218 to yield 198. The total number of legs of kangaroo and the goats is 322.<n><n>The fourth multiple choice question requires us finding how much money Josh has left after buying a hat, pencil, and cookies each costing $1.25. Josh started with $20 and had extra money since he bought a cookie. Josh spent 10 dollars to buy a hat and a pencil, so Josh has $20 - 10 - $2 = $7 left.<n><n>After round 9, they need to beat the league record by 291, which requires them to play a total of 1,059 points. In order for each person to finish the round, they would have to beat the current league record by 269 points. Each person needs to earn 269 points in an individual round for the total to add up to

Choices: A: study hard B: relax C: do the work<n>Output: A<n><n>## Example:<n>Input: Mary had x stickers. She used y stickers on the front and z stickers to the rest of her journal, thus x - y < 6 and x - z >= 3, which means we get 89 - 3 < 6 and 89 - z >= 3.<n>x = 89 - (3 + 6 - 3) = 84, which gives us answer.<n>For second problem: Zach needs to work 6 more hours to get his allowance to cover the complete cost of bicycle.<n><n>## Author:<n><n>### Problem 1:<n><n>### Q1:<n><n>## Solutions:<n>

")<n>if answer == out:<n>    print("Correct!")<n># ---------------------- #<n><n><n># print(answer)<n><n># if out == "E" and answer == "E":<n>#     print("Correct! I also spent $14 on lunch every day since I had no money set aside for that.  How much money did I have left at the end of the semester?<n>Output: -4.01<n><n>Input: 2^3 + 2^5 + 1^6 How many bits?<n><n>Output: 14<n><n>Input: What is 5^1 - 2^4 in binary<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: 6^6+10^9 = 4<n>Input: 15^863 = 0(?)<n>Output: 1

It can be done by finding the amount of money left after mowing the lawn. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:She a deep love for all her friends, every Friday she had an open invitation for them as she loved to host and what? How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. Mary had 89 **** stickers.  She ***used 3*** large stickers on the *** front page of her journal *** and 7 stickers ***each*** to ***6 ***other pages of her journal. ***How many stickers does Mary ***have remaining***? 44 <n><n>- 89 -> 72 //72 + 19<n><n>- 19 -> 15 //15 + 4<n><n>- 15 -> 6 // 6 + 9<n><n>- 6 -> 4 // 4 + 12<n><n>2. Zach is saving his $$$ to buy a brand new*** bike*** that costs $10***.  His weekly allow***ance is $**5***.  His parent will pay ***him an extra $**10*** to mow the la***wn***.  His neighbor will pay ***him $**7*** per ***hour***** to ***babysit*** ***their son***.  He has ***already saved up $**65***. He'll receive his $$ allowance*** on Friday and he'***s planning on bab*** sitting for 2 hours this ****Saturday**** after he mows the $$ lawn***. How much more money does ***Zach*** need to earn before ***he can buy the bike***? ***6***. <n><n>100-65=35<n><n>100=35*1+35<n><n>35=1+35<n>35=35<n>35/1=35<n><n>322<n><n>322=123(kangaroo) + 210(goat)<n><n>2.322=23+6<n><n>2.332=123*2+100*4<n><n>3. George's bowling ***team***/ ***is one round*** away from broken the league record for most ***points ****scored in a season. The ***old record*** is an average ***score per player of 2**

If the remainder is zero then your result is prime number. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Where would you see people in uniform playing with a ball? Choices:  A: hole B: television C: sporting goods store D: pool table E: sporting event<n>Output:		Sporting event\<n><n>### Solution: Answer the following multiple choice question<n><n>The total number of legs of Mark's animals is 23+3 times (23/6). That gets you 39/2, or 19 1/2, then round down to 19.<n><n>Josh has $20 left. He spent $22. We can subtract the $22 from the $20, and get that he has $8 left. 8<n><n># George's bowling record<n>George's team scored 10,454 points. His team needs -180 points per game to tie the record. The team's average at this point is 292.1, rounded up to 293. Each player has an average of 293 pts per player. The difference between his average and the record is -27.<n><n>George is short by 27 points, so his average must be something higher than 293 because 27 is less than 3.<n><n>Sophia's answer is 240. Her pie can only be weighed as being at 1200.0 because of the decimal point in pounds. <n><n>Sarah, Mary, and Touan each contributed 21$ so that 67 divided by 4 gave them 16.875, then they rounded each number as being 17. <n><n>### Code:<n><n>### Output:<n><n>```python<n>>>> TotalLegs = input().split(','))   #TotalLegs is a list of animals in the farm<n>>>> FinalLegs = TotalLegs[0] + TotalLegs[1] + TotalLegs<n>>>> TotalLeg = int(FinalLegs) <n>```<n><n>```Pytthon<n>>>> TotalMoney = input().split( "," )[0]   #TotalMoney is the initial amount<n>>>> TotalMoneys = int(TotalMoney)<n>>>> TotalMones - TotalMoney<n>>>> print( 'Josh doesn't have enough money. He should not go shopping.' )<n>```<n><n>```python<n># For this problem statement, you are given a variable that tells you the number of players on a bowling team

How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:There weren't potatoes but actually a snake in his what? Choices:  A: burlap sack B: hot country C: purse D: pet shops E: deep grass<n>Output:		D: Pet Shops<n><n>Input:There were 8 apples, 5 oranges and 3 pears in a basket. He took 1 apple, 1 orange and 1 pear out.  How many apples, oranges and pears remained in the basket?<n>Output: 7<n>2<n>3<n><n>Input: There were 11 donuts in a box. 7 of them were chocolate donuts and the remaining were  fruit donuts.  Everyone wanted a chocolate donut, but no one wanted a fruit donut.  What about the remaining 3 donuts?<n>Output: B : 2 chocolate 1 fruit<n><n>Input:If an elephant drinks 100 liters of water in one day, how much water does he drink in 2 days?<n>Output: 80<n><n>Input : 14990.9999<n>Output:  14990<n><n>### What did you learn about math? <n><n>I learned that the main idea is, to get the answer, you have to use your problem solving skills. I learned that if i don't understand a problem, it is always safe to start on small problems that has similar concepts to the big problem i want to solve. <n><n>### Is there anything else you want to share?<n><n>I like how this website helped me solve many problems.

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. Choices:  A: do crossword puzzle B: see art C: give up D: grocery shop E: play chess<n>Output:		A<n><n>### My solution, and explanation of the approach:<n><n>In a journal page, there have a total of 26 rows  and one 26th of the page is for the cover image of journal.<n>First, there are 26 rows in which each cell contains a sticker.<n>Then, there is row for the cover and it has 26 cells. We do not use cells in which the sticker is used.<n><n>To assign the sticker, there are 27 cells in total.(row 1-3 have been covered because row 1 is for the index, and row 3 is for the cover image.)<n><n>Therefore, the number of stickers is 27.<n><n>Bicycle<n>To calculate the total of the money, the following method is used.<n>We have some known values, namely current money of Zach = $65 and amount of money for each babysit = $7.<n>To solve the problem, we have two questions:<n>1. How much money more Zach needs to earn?<n>2. How much time he needs after he babysit after mowing the lawn?<n><n>So first, We have known the total amount of money Zach needs to earn = $100.<n>Hence $100 = T<n><n>We can say $100 = $68+$32.<n>Hence $68 = Y, $32 = Z<n><n>We can say that after babysit, money of Zach = $ (65+ (3*7))+5 dollars = $82+15 = $97.<n>Now, the babysitting times for one day, is given by,<n><n>$$ \therefore T = T-5 $$<n><n>Or, this can be written as<n>$$ T = (32-26) = 6 $$<n><n>Hence, Zach needs 6 hours of babysitting after he babysitting after mowing the lalwn.<n><n>Goats<n>To calculate the total number of legs in animals, first, we need to split the animals in terms of Kangaroos and goat.<n><n>$$ \therefor\ Kangaroos= 23-3=15-3=3/2 $$<n><n>$$ \sum Kangaroo legs =6
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. One of them goes to the 5th floor, one of them goes to the ground floor and the third button goes to the 7th floor. There’s only a single elevator, they take turns and only go in the direction of increasing numbers. How many trips do you need to take to get to the 7th Floor?<n>Output: 7<n><n>Input:Increasing numbers are: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7. Which floor is the closest to the 5th?<n>Output: 5
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:What is a place where you usually store dishes but not books? Choices:  A: apartment B: pantry C: table D: living room E: shelf<n>Output:		 C<n><n>Input:I am a person. I am not a dog. All dogs are animals. However, not all animals are dogs.<n>Output:  I am a person. I can speak english but I don't eat meat<n><n>Input:What do we call someone who is very smart and handsome?  Choices: A: Beautiful man B: Intelligent guy C: Beautiful lady D: Smart Boy<n>Output:  I'm both an intelligent guy and a beautiful lady.<n><n>Input:The number of books I bring on a trip. It starts at 0 and after each day it's always doubled and added to the original value. How many books do I have after 5 days?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input:Sarah had $8 left after paying $3.50 for gas, $2.50 for pizza. How much money did she have in the beginning?<n>Output: 8.50 <n>

We'll demonstrate how much work and memory 2038 can handle, depending on the size of the problems. <n> <n><n>##### Step 1<n>Run `python main.py` and observe the output of the calculator.<n><n>##### Step1<n><n>##### Step2<n>Let's say the numbers we are adding up are in the array variable `user_input_numbers`. <n><n>We can ask the array size using `user_input_number.len()`.<n><n>If the array is empty, it only has length 0.<n><n>##### Tutorial<n><n>##### For each input we are going to try a few different scenarios to explain how much of what you're thinking through matters in regards to problem size.<n><n>##### If the array isn't empty:<n><n>The first question we need to answer is the length of the array.<n><n>##### For our purposes:<n><n>Our two arrays never will have an equal number of numbers.<n><n><n><n>#### How Much Work:<n><n>An array can hold at most a maximum of 100,000 numbers.<n><n>A memory storage of 4 GB works with 20 digit numbers, where 256 digit numbers requires 8 GB. <n><n>When comparing apples to oranges it's best to think of them as 1.7 GB. <n><n>How Big is 100,200? <n><n>```<n>len(numbers)  <n>99,999  <n>```<n><n>Is it a bit more or a bit less? <n><n>```console<n>%python<n>print(len(numbers) / 3)<n>>><n>3,000<n>```<n>That means 3,000 numbers, which is a lot.  <n><n>If we were to add up a million digits in our array,<n><n>The array would take up 1.7 GB on average. A million isn't that far off from 10,000. <n><n><n><n><n><n>An `if` statement works like this: <n><n>```<n>if(condition)<n>  output<n>else: <n>  output<n><n>if(condition) {<n>  len(numbers)<n>}

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:What do you fill with ink to print? Choices:  A: squid B: pencil C: newspaper D: fountain pen E: printer<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input:What's the total number of sides that a cube, a pyramid, and a frustum have? Choices: 1: 10 2: 6 3: 5 4: 8<n>Output: 3: 5<n><n>Input:How many 5s are less than 400? Choices: 0: none 1: 2 2: 3 3: 4 4: 5<n>Output: 3 4: 5 5: 2<n><n>Input: You need 4 pieces of cloth, but you don't need any more than 3 red pieces and you need 3 pieces. Choices: 5: Rhombus 6: Triangle 7: Square 8: Pentagon<n>Output: 5 6 7 8<n><n>Input: What is the value of 6x - 4y in the equation 6x - 5y = 10? Your solution length is "<n>                  // + caseValue<n>                  + (answerInput1 * answerInput1));<n>      System.out = scanner;<n>    } else if(answer.equals('3')){<n>      caseValue++; // should be increased??????<n>      int answerInput;<n>      int answerOutput;<n>      answerInput = scanner<n>         .nextInt();<n>      answerOutput = answerInput + answerInput * answerInput;<n>      answerOutput = (long) Math.sqrt(answerOutput);<n>      System.out(<n>          "Your answer is " + ((int) Math.pow(Math.pow((double) answerOutput, answerOutput) - answerOutput)) + "! Your solution"<n>              + " length is " + (answerInput * answerInput));<n>      System.nout.println();<n>      System.out= scanner;<n>  }

Choices:  A: gas stations B: city C: london D: train station E: airport<n>Output:		A<n><n>### Question 1<n><n>`<n>int main()<n>{<n>  int i;<n>  scanf("%d",i);// Reads in i<n>  if(i==89)<n>  {<n>    printf("correct");<n>    return 0;<n>  }<n>  else<n>  {<n>    if(i<0)<n>    {<n>      printf("wrong");<n>      return 0;<n>    }<n>  }<n>}`<n><n>-<n>The program is incorrect.<n><n>-<n><n>### Question2<n><n>`<n>int sum;<n>int i;<n>scanf("%d",i,sum);<n>for(int j=0;j<i;j++)<n>{<n>  sum=sum/2;<n>  printf("%d\n",i);<n>}`<n><n>### Question3<n><n>`<n>int ans;<n>for(int i=1;i<=2;i++)<n>{<n>  if(i>j)<n>  ans++;<n>}<n>printf("%d",j-ans);`<n><n>-<n>The answer for this test case is<n><n>-<n><n><br><a href="https://github.com/hackerearth">The Solution</a>.<n>

Coding Task: A new application will use a `Food` class,  and a `Pizza` class. `Menu` is a list of Pizzas, each with an `item` field and a `cost` field. In the `Food` class the method `orderFood()` adds any food in the `meal` list to the cart and inverses its cost in the current session. `cart.orderFood()` adds the cost of the meals (which is in the `cart`) to the total cost. The method `orderTotal()` adds the costs from the cart and the `meals` and the method `returnValue()` returns the total value of the cart and the meal at the end of the session.<n><n>```<n>class Food {<n>    menu: Menu[]<n>    constructor(){<n>        this.menu = []<n>    }<n><n>    placeOrder(meal: Menu): void {<n>        this.menu.push(meal)<n>    }<n><n>getOrderTotal(): void {<n>cart = {}<n>    for (let meal of this.menu) {<n>        cart[meal.item] = meal.cost<n>    }<n>    this.orderTotal()<n>    for (const item of cart.keys()) {<n>        this.orderTotal(cart[item])<n>        }<n>    }<n>    }<n>```<n>```<n>class Menu{<n>    get item():void {<n>        if (this.item === 'pizza'){<n>            return 'order a delicious pizza'<n>        }else {<n>            return 'order another meal other than pizza'<n>        }}<n><n>    constructor(item: string){<n>        this.item = item<n>    }<n><n>}<n>```<n><n>```<n>class Pizza {<n>    constructor(item?: string, cost?: number) {<n>        this.item= item || 'pepperoni pizza.';<n>        this.cost = cost || 13;<n><n>    }<n>```

How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: 322<n><n>Input: Josh’s mom gives him $20 to go shopping at the mall. He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Mary wasn't familiar with James, so she wasn't comfortable speaking with him. How might she come off? Choices:  A: cold B: unfamiliar C: unknown D: unacquainted E: shy<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input: There's an odd number of coins in my pocket. I know there are more quarters than nickels and fewer nickels than dimes. There are probably a half dollar and a penny in there too. How many coins do I have if I know it is an odd number?<n>Output: 7<n><n>Input: Dustin wanted to make a game to practice his geometry for his finals. He decided to play the game so it was easy to remember. He decided to come up with a game related to area of a rectangle. He started with an image of a rectangle and then used his favorite colorful crayons. He colored in a different amount of the rectangle for each problem type. So for instance, if the problem was a length x width problem, half the rectangle would be colored. If the problem was a length and width problem, the rectangle would be one fifth of the rectangle colored. If the problem has three measurements, like x, y, and z, he would color in the rectangle to be half its length.  What is the most points for one game?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: I know the total value of a set of coins, like pennies and dollars. I know the set is 15 coins and that it has a minimum of 5 pennies. I also know the coins must be all of one type. For example it cannot have one quarter, three nickels, and six pennies.What is the fewest type of coins I need to be able to determine if it is the minimum value or not?<n>Output: D<n><n>Input: There are 15 coins in total and there must be 5 cents.<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: You need to do 5 times 330 = 1650 times.<n>Output: 1650<n><n>Input:"My son bought 12 soccer balls during his birthday. All we have to do is subtract 3 from 89, which is easy to do in our head.  We then take the difference (44) and compare it to the number of remaining stickers: 44 - 6 = 38.  That's how many we used initially, so how many are left?  44 - 38 is 6.  Mary has 6 stickers left.<n>

Choices:  A: fearless B: english carrier C: courageous D: brave E: achromatic<n>Output:		C <n><n>Instruction:This is a single choice question.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the programming question below.<n><n>-   [ ] [ ] [ ] [X] [X] [X][X][X]<n><n>Input: "A" represents the string "Apple", "B" represents the string "Banana", "c" represents the string "Cantaloupe", and so on. Write a program that accepts "A", "B", "c", etc. as inputs and determines whether the next item in the list of items is the one that comes after the item before it (i.e. 'B' is the next word, if the item before was 'A' and 'B' is the third item of the list). The answer must be "true" if the next item is the one that comes immediately after the item before it, and "false" otherwise.<n>Output: A[1], B[2], c[3], etc.<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>```javascript<n>/*<n>    Example: A[2] => true<n>    Example: A  :true<n>    Example: A : true<n> */<n>function solution(a, b, c) {<n>    try {<n>        <n>        // If c is the next item in the string, <n>        // if a is the next character in string,<n>        // if b is the next character in the string,<n>        return [a.length === c.length? c[1] === b.next() : a[1] === b[1], false]<n>    } catch (err) {<n>        console.log(err);<n>        return;<n>    }<n>}<n>```<n><n>### Solution 2:<n><n>```javascript                     <n>function mySlice( a, b ) {<n>    if((b-a)[1] === 1){<n>        return false;<n>    }else{<n>        return  (a[1] === b)? true : <n>        mySlice(a[1], a[1].next());<n>    }<n>}                <n>```<n><n>## Instruction: This is a multiple choice question<n><n>## Instruction (2, 3): Answer the programming or the mathematical questions below.<n><n>## Instruction(1): Answer the programming questions below. <n><n>## Instruction :Answer the questions below<n><n>

It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:If you see blinking lights in the air at night, what are you usually looking at? Choices:  A: carnival B: plane C: concert D: turned at night E: a penguin's bum<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: The average of 6 numbers is 10.3. Three of these numbers are 3, 5, 7. Find the average of the other three numbers?<n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: The sum of five different numbers is 98. How old is the youngest of these numbers?<n>Output: 8<n>```<n><n><n><n>#### My answer:<n>```typescript<n>class Solution {<n>    constructor(private memory: Array<number[]>){<n>    }<n><n>    public FindContentChildren(input) {<n>        const total = 100;<n>        let child = 1;<n>        let p = 0;<n>        this.memory[child] = input.slice(0, total);<n>        while (p < total) {<n>            // console.log(parseInt(p));<n>            if(input > this.memory[parseInt(p)][0]) {<n>                p++;<n>            } else {<n>                if(p == 0)<n>                {child++;}<n>                else<n>                {<n>                    p = child;<n>                }<n>            }<n>        }<n>        return child;<n>    }<n>}<n>```
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. They decided to split the cost of the meal evenly. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Sarah thought that she had been home all evening.  That meant that the only time to leave was when? Choices:  A: early morning B: day time C: night D: afternoon E: daytime<n>Output:		Afternoon<n><n>Input: Sarah thought that she had been at the grocery store all morning. That meant that the only times to leave were 1.  early morning, 2. daytime, 3.  night, 4.  daytime, and 5. daytime<n>Output: 2. daytime<n><n>Input: Sarah was at home the next morning and all day and night and afternoon.  Then she went running.  She then went home and went to the grocery store.  From the grocery store she went to work.  How many times will Sarah have been away from home if she has only been home before her run and after she returned from to the grocery?<n>Output: 7<n><n>Input: Sarah got a message from her friend that said she needed to be at the park at 6. Sarah thought she could go to the grocery and pick up ingredients for dinner. She decided to go immediately.  If it took Sarah 26 minutes to get to the grocery, how many minutes has it been since her friend left the message?<n>Output: 9<n>

He buys a hat for $10 and a pencil for $2. Then he buys four cookies. If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. The old record is an average score per player of 287 per round. Each team has 4 players and there are 10 rounds in the season. Through the first 9 rounds, his team has scored a total of 10,440. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. It took him 20 minutes to finish tasks from biology and two times more time to finish history. Geography took him the most time, three times more than history. How much time did Max spend on doing his homework?<n>Output: 180<n><n>Input: Sophia ate 1/6 of her pie and she put the rest on the fridge. If the pie left in the fridge weighs 1200 grams, how many grams did Sophia eat?<n>Output: 240<n><n>Input: Sarah, Mary, and Tuan decided to go to the restaurant for a meal. If the total price of the meal comes to $67 and they have a coupon for $4, how much does each person need to contribute to the bill?<n>Output: 21<n><n>Input:Bill bought an upright piano but didn't have anywhere to put it because he lived where? Choices:  A: band B: music room C: college D: university E: house<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input:Jeff had a large sum of money.He bought a large house for 125000$.Which number is 10% more than that amount (a) 1450. (c) 32500 (b) 13075 (d) 132500 Output for me 21000 which is right a??<n><n>```<n>class Solution {<n>public:<n>    int answer(string s, string word){<n>        vector <int> a; //index of letter, int of count<n>        for (int i = 0; i < word.size(); i++)<n>            a.push_back(a.size());<n>        for (auto c : s)<n>            a[a.size() - 1] += c == word[i]? -1:1;<n>        int x = a[0];<n>        for (size_t i = 1; i < a.size(); i++) {<n>            if (x > a[i])<n>                x = a[i];<n>            else<n>                x += a[i];  <n>        }<n>        if (x>0)<n>            return x;<n>        else<n>            return -x;        <n>    }<n>};<n>```

Input: Mary had 87 stickers.  She cut 3 large stickers into 12 pieces and 7 stickers into two pieces each. How many stickers remain?<n><n>```python<n>stickers = 87<n># 3 large stickers<n>stickers += sticker * (3/10)<n># 1 large sticker and 6 pieces of <n># 2 small stickers<n>p1 = (sticker - 1) * 12 / 6<n>p2 = 12 * 6 / 7<n>s1 = p1 + p2<n># 1 large and 7 small stickers<n>s2 = 7 * sticker * 6<n>stickers += s1 - p2<n><n>stickers<n>```<n><n>2. Input: Zach is saving his $5 to buy a brand new $100 bike.  He'll get $5 on Friday for babysitting for the neighbor.  He has $65 in his piggy bank. How much more money does he need?<n><n>```python <n># he'll get more money but also save some stickers<n>moneyInThePiggyBank = 65<n>moneyFromTheNeighbor = 10<n># how much he spent from his piggy bank every week<n>allowance = 5<n>totalMoneySpent = 5  + allowance<n>numberOfStickers = stickers(100) - stickers * (allowance/10)<n><n># the amount of money (allowance) - difference between sticker price<n>extraMoneyNeeded = moneyInThePiggyBasin - numberOfStickers + totalMoneySpent<n>```<n><n>3. Input: Mark has kangaroo and goats.  There are 23 kangaroo. The total number of legs of Kangaroos is 214 (2 legs * 23).  There are a tripple of number of legs of the go

If each cookie costs $1.25, how much money does Josh have left?<n>Output: 3<n><n>Input: George's bowling team is one round away from breaking the league record for most points scored in a season. How many points less than the current league record per game average is the minimum average they need to score, per player, in the final round to tie the league record?<n>Output: 27<n><n>Input: Max was doing homework in three different subjects. [A to B]<n><n>**Easy**<n>```python<n>def easyQuestion():<n>    input = raw_input()<n>    answer = raw_input(input)<n><n>if easyQuestion() == answer.upper():<n>    print 'CORRECT!'<n>elif answer!= answer.upper():<n>	print 'WRONG...'<n>else: <n>    print 'YOU FAILED!'<n>```<n><n>**Hard**<n>```python<n>import operator # PLEASE PASTE PYTHON FILE INTO NOTEPAD, CLICK ESC, AND PASTE ITS CONTENTS AFTER SCRUBBER, AND PRESS "NEXT" BUTTON FIRST, THEN "SCRUB" BUTTON TO RUN TEST CASES.<n>print 'What should you do if the train is full?'<n>def hardQuestion():<n>    ans1 = input().split()<n>    print 'There are '+ans1[0]+' people in the first car'<n>    ans2 = input().split() + ans1[0]<n>    print 'There is '+ans2[2]+' people in the second car'<n>    ans3 = input().split() <n>    print 'There's  '+ans3[1]+' kids'<n>    ans4 = input().split()+ans3[1]<n>    print 'Things  '+ans4[0]+' are'<n>    ans5 = input().split()[1:len(input())]<n>    print '.'<n>if hardQuestion() == ans1 + ans2 + ans3 + ans4 + ans5: #ANSWER 1, ANSWER 2, ANSWER TOGETHER, AND FINAL ANSWER FORMATION<n>    print 'Congratulations!'<n>    print 'You can work at the train station'<n>else:<n>    print 'Nobody is going to hire you.'<n>```<n><n>**Medium**<n>```python<n>input = raw_input() # PLEASE PAST EXERCISES TO NOTEPAD, COMMIT IT AND CHECK ANSWERS<n>if eval(input).strip():<n>    print('
